TI  - Structure, actors, and interdependencies between informal and formal e-waste management supply chain in Bangladesh
AU  - Akter, Nasrin
AU  - Hossain, Muhammad I.
T2  - JOURNAL OF CLEANER PRODUCTION
AB  - The informal supply chain (SC) of electronic waste (e-waste) is causing significant environmental and health hazards; however, its contributions to managing most e-waste in developing countries are undeniable. Although its dominant co-existence with the formal SC of e-waste is well-acknowledged, including the specifics and the nuances, limited knowledge exists on how the two channels interact and complement each other while creating value for the SC. This qualitative study focuses on informal and formal e-waste management SC in Bangladesh. We combine data collected through 138 interviews from a multitude of direct actors involved in informal and formal e-waste management SC. Our data explains-a) how e-waste moves across various tiers of the informal and formal supply chain and impacts e-waste management; b) how values are created and delivered within both chains; and c) what triggers the interdependence between the chains. Among other observations, our findings suggest the impact of socioeconomic status on households' choice of e-waste disposal methods and informal channel actors' choice to engage in recycling activities. Theoretically, our study adds new knowledge regarding the factors that motivate e-waste management actors to engage in recycling activities beyond financial gain. The knowledge on multi-party and multi-stage cooperation and competition, as provided in this study, also extended the role-based literature on e-waste management actors, providing policymakers strategic insights to identify potential integration loops between Bangladesh's informal and formal e-waste management SC.
